Hitherto we have seen that in ordinary cases Greek Unaccented a, ε, ο, ι, υ correspond to the same vowels in Latin. ln some vowels. cases however special laws intervene to prevent the corres- pondence being complete, as when a Greek ου becomes in - Latin auor ελ becomes ol. ln unaccented syllables in Latin the vowels tended to lose their proper sound and approximate to that ol the indeterminate vowel, andare then at the mercy of the surrounding consonants‚ and are treated in the same way 'as an indeterminate vowel inherited from the original language. It is noticeable that in Greek vowels are not in. any way affected by the presence or absence of the accent.

Exceptions to the regular representation of vowels in un- accented syllables are due to various causes. In some cases the archaic pronunciation and spelling is preserved, asin quaesumus, volumus, where u represents the Greek 0, which ordinarily becomes in Latin i. Sumus, if an enclitic, ought to become simus, and this ¹is actually the way it was spelt by Augustus But u tends to be maintained in such cases in initial syllables-cf. labet beside aber.
